  <h2>High-Yield Savings vs. Other Options</h2>

  <h3>High-Yield Savings vs. CDs</h3>
  <p>Certificates of deposit often offer slightly higher rates but lock your money for a fixed term — typically three months to five years. If you need flexibility, a high-yield savings account wins. If you have money you won't touch for a year or more, a CD might earn you an extra 0.25-0.50% APY.</p>

  <h3>High-Yield Savings vs. Money Market Accounts</h3>
  <p>Money market accounts function similarly to high-yield savings but sometimes include check-writing privileges and debit cards. Rates are comparable. Choose a money market account if you want easier spending access; choose high-yield savings if you want to keep your savings separate from spending temptations.</p>

  <h3>High-Yield Savings vs. Treasury Bills</h3>
  <p>T-bills are backed by the US government and can offer competitive yields. However, they require purchasing through TreasuryDirect or a brokerage, and your money is locked until maturity. For pure liquidity and simplicity, high-yield savings accounts are hard to beat.</p>

